          <source>How to: Determine Which TreeView Node Was Clicked (Windows Forms)</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>When working with the Windows Forms <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.TreeView&gt;</ph> control, a common task is to determine which node was clicked, and respond appropriately.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>To determine which TreeView node was clicked</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Use the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.EventArgs&gt;</ph> object to return a reference to the clicked node object.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Determine which node was clicked by checking the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.TreeViewEventArgs&gt;</ph> class, which contains data related to the event.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>As an alternative, you can use the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.MouseEventArgs&gt;</ph> of the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.MouseDown&gt;</ph> or <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.MouseUp&gt;</ph> event to get the <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Point.X%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id="ph5">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Point.Y%2A&gt;</ph> coordinate values of the <ph id="ph6">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Point&gt;</ph> where the click occurred.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Then, use the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.TreeView&gt;</ph> control's <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.TreeView.GetNodeAt%2A&gt;</ph> method to determine which node was clicked.</source>
        </trans-unit>
